'''Zero-elevation surface''' is a widely accepted vertical reference point that is used to describe a surface, such as that of a [[planet]]. The value of this datum is usually adopted by statute. This elevation is used, for example, to build a texture map from an agreed surface, such as a [[spheroid]] with dimensions defined by a mean [[surface gravity]]. In the case of the [[Earth]], the zero-elevation surface is usually taken as [[sea level]].

